<DOC><DOCNO> AP880512-0060 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-88 0612EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-12 0230</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0244</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Up In Europe, Gold Down</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. dollar gained ground on all other majorcurrencies in light European trading early today. Gold bullionprices drifted lower.   The closure of most European markets for the Ascension Dayholiday brought activity to a near standstill, traders said.British and Italian markets were the only major centers operatingtoday.   The dollar's higher rate reflected gains in New York lateWednesday after major U.S. banks raised their prime lending ratefrom 8.5 percent to 9 percent.   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:   _1.6839 West German marks, up from 1.6773   _1.4015 Swiss francs, up from 1.3935   _5.7100 French francs, up from 5.6912   _1.8870 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8830   _1,251.80 Italian lire, up from 1,249.50   _1.2320 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2315   The British pound fell to $1.8778 from $1.8870.   The dollar firmed to 124.39 Japanese yen in Tokyo, up fromWednesday's close of 124.24 yen. In later London trading today, thedollar was quoted at 124.70 yen.   London's main bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price atmidmorning of $448.65 a troy ounce, down from $449.30 lateWednesday.   Zurich markets were closed for Ascension Day.   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $450.06, downfrom $451.68.   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $6.52 a troy ounce,down from $6.55.</TEXT></DOC>